ce:section.ce:para:
The carbon dots were prepared via a green hydrothermal method using succinic acid and glycerol as novel carbon precursors (Fig. 1
                        ). These are water soluble molecules that can be produced from renewable resources and are readily available. In contrast to several previous reports of the synthesis of carbon dots [54–57], the process developed in this work did not require the use of acid or base catalysts. Our method is thus green, practical, and economical. The precursors were simply heated to 250 °C in a hydrothermal process. After purification, a yield of 25% was obtained, which is comparable with previous studies (Table 1
                        ) and sufficient for large scale production. This is possibly because succinic acid and glycerol are highly reactive and water-soluble monomers. It was found that the emission wavelength of the carbon dots could be tuned simply by varying the reaction time. Under UV illumination, the reaction mixture heated for 6 h produced blue-fluorescent carbon dots, and the reaction mixture heated for 24 h produced green-fluorescent carbon dots. This tunability is beneficial for multi-color sensing and imaging applications.

The FT-IR spectra were obtained and used to investigate the functional groups present in the carbon dots (Fig. 3
                        ). Broad signals at 3450 cm−1 were attributed to O-H stretching vibration. Signals at 1380, 1638, and 2850 cm−1 were characteristic of C-C bending, C=O, and C-H stretching vibration modes, respectively. These FT-IR results suggested the presence of hydrophilic functional groups, including hydroxyl, carboxylate, and carbonyls. A signal of C=O stretching suggested the presence of sp2 carbons responsible for the conjugation within the carbon dot core [61]. The XPS technique was used to investigate the chemical composition of the carbon dots. Blue-emitting carbon dots produced signals at 285.3, 400.3, and 531.3 eV. These were attributed to C1s, N1s, and O1s with atomic concentration of 52.58%, 4.53% and 30.16%, respectively (Fig. 4
                        a). Notably, the nitrogen signal was from the incorporation of nitrogen into the carbon dots via the use of nitric acid as neutralizing agent during synthesis [62]. The high-resolution spectrum of the C1s peak showed the presence of C-C, C-O, and C=O functional groups at 285.0 eV, 286.5 eV, and 288.3 eV (Fig. 4b). In addition, green-emitting carbon dots exhibited signals at 285.2 and 531.2 eV, attributed to C1s and O1s with atomic concentration of 70.33% and 17.81%, respectively (Fig. 4c). The high-resolution spectrum of the C1s peak showed the presence of C-C, C-O, and C=O functional groups at 285.0 eV, 286.2 eV, 286.9, and 288.5 eV (Fig. 4d). The nitrogen signal of the green-emitting carbon dots was almost negligible. It has been known that nitrogen-doped carbon dots are generally blue-emitting, which is consistent with our results [63,64]. Both the FT-IR and XPS results confirmed the presence of hydrophilic oxygen-containing groups [65,66].

The sensitivity of the carbon dot/H2O2 mixture to Fe2+ ions was further investigated by varying the Fe2+ concentration from 1 to 1000 μM. The fluorescent intensity of carbon dots increased as the concentration of Fe2+ was increased (Fig. 8
                        a). The detection limit determined by the 3σ/slope method was 21.9 μM, and a Stern-Volmer plot showed good linearity in the range 10–50 μM (Fig. 8b). This was comparable with results reported from previous studies (Table 2
                        ). The carbon dot/H2O2-coated filter paper was next tested with Fe2+ ions at different concentrations (Fig. 8c) and the images were taken under UV illumination. The image color became distinguishable from the control sample (without Fe2+) at Fe2+ concentrations greater than 50 μM with naked eye inspection. For more accurate color determination, the RGB values of the images were extracted. The RGB values were found to diverge significantly from those of a control sample at 30 μM (Fig. 8d). The carbon dot/H2O2-coated filter paper could effectively sense the Fe2+ at concentrations as low as 30 μM. This result demonstrates that the carbon dots developed in this work would make capable Fe2+ sensors in the micromolar range. In addition to a few reports of carbon dot-based Fe2+ sensors, to the best of our knowledge, our work is the first study to investigate the creation of paper-based Fe2+ sensors from carbon dots.

The previous experiment demonstrated the ability of H2O2 to quench the fluorescence of the carbon dots. As this suggested that the carbon dots are able to detect H2O2 effectively, the use of the carbon dots was investigated as H2O2 sensor. The fluorescence emission intensity was found to decrease as the H2O2 concentration increased (Fig. 9
                        a and b). This may have been due to hydrogen peroxide radicals disrupting the surface states of the carbon dots that produced the fluorescence emissions [52]. Using the 3σ/slope method, the detection limit was determined to be 0.7 μM, comparable with previous reports (Table 3
                        ). A linear Stern-Volmer plot suggests a static quenching mechanism of carbon dots by H2O2. Carbon dot-coated filter paper was tested at different concentrations of H2O2 (Fig. 9c), with images taken under UV irradiation. Again, the image color became distinguishable from the control sample (without H2O2) at H2O2 concentrations greater than 700 nM, consistent with the detection limit, with naked eye inspection. This result suggested that our paper-based carbon dot sensors are able to detect H2O2 at concentrations as low as 700 nM using naked eyes. RGB values diverged significantly from those of a control sample at an H2O2 concentration of approximately 400 nM (Fig. 9d). The selectivity and sensitivity of the carbon dots to both Fe2+ ions and H2O2, and their turn-on and turn-off fluorescent behavior, suggests potential as dual-mode sensors in the sub-micromolar concentration. The carbon dots demonstrated in this study could provide portable, non-toxic sensors for the qualitative and quantitative determination of ferrous ion and H2O2 levels in water bodies and industrial wastes and find applications in a range of industrial and biological fields.

To further evaluate the practical applications of carbon dots as H2O2 and Fe2+ ion sensors, water from local river, tap water, mineral bottled water, and drinking bottled water were used as media. As these water samples might not contain H2O2 and Fe2+ ions, the water samples were spiked with H2O2 (0.1, 1, 10 μM) and Fe2+ (500 μM) solutions. The fluorescence intensities were measured for calculating the recovery in percentage using samples prepared in DI water as the standard. The recoveries of H2O2 were between 95.4 and 104.5% with relative standard deviation (RSD) less than 2.14% for all four types of real water samples at three different concentrations of H2O2 (Table 5

                        ). Similarly, the recoveries of Fe2+ were between 95.1 and 105.0% with RSD less than 1.59% for all samples (Table 6
                        ). These results indicated that our carbon dots could detect H2O2 and Fe2+ in real water samples with high accuracy and repeatability and can potentially be used for sensing in various applications.
